--------------------------------
What is ReactJs ? 
-------------------------------
ReactJS is an open-source JavaScript library developed by Facebook for building fast, scalable, and reusable user interfaces, mainly for single-page applications (SPAs).

React helps us to build UI's declaratively .

React use virtual dom to optimise performance .
  
Instead of manually changing the DOM, React uses a virtual DOM to decide the fastest way to update the page.

 Virtual DOM : 
-------------------------------
React creates a virtual copy of the DOM

When data changes, React:

              Updates the virtual DOM
  
              Compares it with the previous version

              Updates only what changed in the real DOM

This makes React fast and efficient.

-----------------------------------
Why ReactJS was introduced
-----------------------------------
1. Problem with traditional DOM manipulation

Earlier, developers directly updated the real DOM

Frequent DOM updates were slow and inefficient

Complex UIs became hard to manage

â¡ï¸ React introduced the Virtual DOM to update only what changes.

2. Difficulty managing large, dynamic UIs

Applications like Facebook had:

Real-time updates

Large amounts of changing data

MVC frameworks became complex and error-prone

â¡ï¸ React simplified UI development using components.

---------------------------------
Advantages of ReactJS : 
---------------------------------
High performance due to Virtual DOM

Reusable components

SEO-friendly (with SSR like Next.js)

Large ecosystem and community

--------------------------------
History of ReactJS
---------------------------------
1. Origin at Facebook (2011)

React was created by Jordan Walke, a software engineer at Facebook

Facebook faced issues managing complex, fast-changing UIs (news feed updates, notifications)

Traditional MVC frameworks were slow and hard to scale

â¡ï¸ React was built to solve performance and UI consistency problems

2. First internal use

React was first used internally on Facebookâ€™s News Feed

Later adopted by Instagram

3. Open-sourced (2013)

Facebook open-sourced React in 2013

Initially met with skepticism because of JSX

Gradually gained popularity due to performance and simplicity

4. Introduction of the Virtual DOM

One of Reactâ€™s biggest innovations

Allowed efficient updates without directly manipulating the real DOM

5. Growth and ecosystem expansion

Community adoption grew rapidly

Tools and libraries emerged:

Redux (state management)

React Router (routing)

Next.js (server-side rendering)

6. Introduction of Hooks (2019)

React 16.8 introduced Hooks

Allowed state and lifecycle features in functional components

Reduced dependency on class components

7. Modern React (Present)

Emphasis on:

Functional components

Hooks

Concurrent rendering

Used by major companies like:

Facebook (Meta)

Netflix

Airbnb

