----------------------------------------------
Basic Structure of ReactJs : 
------------------------------------------------
import { createRoot } from "react-dom/client";

const root = createRoot(document.getElementById("root"));
root.render(<App />);


Line-by-line Explanation : 
--------------------------------
1. Importing createRoot
import { createRoot } from "react-dom/client";
-------------------------------------------------

Imports the React 18 API for rendering React applications

react-dom/client connects React with the browser DOM

createRoot enables concurrent rendering

ğŸ“Œ Interview keyword: Concurrent Mode

2. Accessing the DOM element
document.getElementById("root")
--------------------------------------

Selects the HTML element:

<div id="root"></div>


This is the mounting point for the React app

3. Creating a React root
const root = createRoot(document.getElementById("root"));
-----------------------------------------------------------

Creates a React root object

Tells React where to render the UI

React now controls everything inside the #root div

4. Rendering the App component
root.render(<App />);
-----------------------------------------------

Renders the App component inside the root

<App /> is the entry component

React converts JSX into DOM elements and displays them

What happens internally?

React creates a Virtual DOM

Compares it using diffing

Updates only changed parts in the real DOM


-------------------JSX (Interview-oriented explanation)-------------------------------------
What is JSX?
---------------
JSX (JavaScript XML) is a syntax extension for JavaScript used in React that allows us to write HTML-like code inside JavaScript.

ğŸ‘‰ Browsers do not understand JSX directly â€” it is converted into JavaScript by Babel.
-------------------------
Why JSX was introduced
------------------------
Makes UI code readable

Combines logic and UI in one place

Reduces complex React.createElement() calls
---------------------
Example
JSX code

const element = <h1>Hello React</h1>;

Without JSX (behind the scenes)
const element = React.createElement("h1", null, "Hello React");
------------------------------------------------------------------

JSX Rules (Very important for interviews)
---------------------------------------------

1. Single Parent Element
return (
  <div>
    <h1>Hello</h1>
    <p>World</p>
  </div>
);


(or use fragments <> </>)

2. className instead of class
<div className="container"></div>

3. JavaScript inside { }
<h2>{2 + 3}</h2>

4. Self-closing tags
<img src="logo.png" />

5. Inline styles as objects
<div style={{ color: "red", fontSize: "20px" }}></div>

-------------------------
Advantages of JSX
-------------------------
Better readability

Faster development

Easier debugging

Encourages component-based design

------------------------------
Disadvantages (Interview bonus)
----------------------------
Requires compilation

Mixing HTML with JS may feel confusing initially

----------------how HTML, CSS, and JSX are linked together in a React (Vite) project.-------------------------------------

1ï¸âƒ£ HTML â†’ React (Entry point)
---------------------------------
index.html
<body>
  <div id="root"></div>
  <script type="module" src="/src/main.jsx"></script>
</body>

Role
-----
This is the only HTML file

<div id="root"></div> is where the entire React app loads

It links React using:

<script src="/src/main.jsx"></script>

â¡ï¸ HTML â†’ JSX connection happens here


2ï¸âƒ£ JSX â†’ React Components
-------------------------------
main.jsx
import React from "react";
import { createRoot } from "react-dom/client";
import App from "./App.jsx";

createRoot(document.getElementById("root")).render(<App />);

Role
--------
Connects React to HTML

Renders <App /> inside #root

â¡ï¸ JSX controls what appears inside HTML


3ï¸âƒ£ JSX â†” JSX (Component interaction)
--------------------------------------
App.jsx
import Header from "./Header.jsx";

function App() {
  return (
    <>
      <Header />
      <h1>Hello React</h1>
    </>
  );
}

export default App;

Role
------
Components interact via:
Props
State


4ï¸âƒ£ CSS â†’ JSX (Styling connection)
======================================

Method 1: Global CSS
---------------------
// main.jsx
import "./index.css";

Applies styles to all components.


Method 2: Component CSS
------------------------------
// App.jsx
import "./App.css";


Method 3: Inline styles
---------------------------------
<h1 style={{ color: "red" }}>Hello</h1>


